'''''Absolver''''' is a [[martial arts]]-themed [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing]] video game developed by Sloclap and published by [[Devolver Digital]] for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]. In the game, players control warrior characters who fight other players and [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|computer-controlled characters]] across the fictional land of Adal to prove their worthiness of joining the Absolver peacekeepers. The game's story is focused on the human development of the characters as they fight to find their place in the collapsed empire.{{r|Fextralife: interview}} The character's fighting moves are customized in a "combat deck" of cards, with each card assigned to a move. Players earn cards, equipment, and weapons by progressing through the game.

Sloclap, a Parisian indie game developer composed of former [[Ubisoft Paris]] employees, began work on ''Absolver'' in May 2015. Their core game concept was to have fluid, dynamic movement, similar to dance. The game debuted a year later at the [[2016 Electronic Entertainment Expo]] and was released in August 2017.

== Gameplay ==
{{Multiple image
| direction = vertical
| width = 250
| image1 = Absolver sword draw.gif
| image2 = Absolver flying kick.gif
| footer = Animated gameplay
}}
''Absolver'' is an [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing]] game based on martial arts fighting, featuring a seamless  [[open world]] with shortcuts and free-roaming, and merging single, cooperative and competitive play in the same campaign, which is played from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]].{{r|Fextralife: interview}} Players build custom [[Combo (video gaming)|combinations]] of strikes, [[Parry (fencing)|parries]], and [[feints]] to fight other players and [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|computer-controlled characters]].{{r|Polygon: Soulsinspired}} Players control warrior characters known as Prospects who travel the fictional land of Adal to fight other players and prove their worth to become one of the Absolver peacekeepers. Players progress through the game to [[unlockable (gaming)|unlock]] new armor and equipment, combat styles, and weapons,{{r|VideoGamer.com: announces}} usually as "loot" dropped by defeated enemies.{{r|Digital Trends: complexity}} The game has minor [[massively multiplayer online game]] elements, including the feature of fighting alongside other players on quests and of directly fighting other players in [[player versus player]] match-ups.{{r|PC Gamer: Enigmatic}} Players can also spar with others to teach their characters skills.{{r|Digital Trends: complexity}}

Players customize their characters' fighting moves{{emdash}}known as a move set{{emdash}}by adding and removing cards in a "combat deck", with each card assigned to a specific move. Additionally, players switch between four fighting stances during combat, which changes the moves available to the player.{{r|Gamasutra: Deckbuilding}} Each fighting stance has two attacks, each with its own controller button. Players earn additional cards by progressing through the game. Each card has a numerical rating for speed and damage dealt as well as secondary functions, such as the ability to break an opponent's guard. The moves in each stance can be set such that the player can switch between stances during a single combination of attacks to have the guard-breaking or absorption-interrupting moves that work best against the opponent's play style.{{r|GamesRadar: timing}} The character can also equip a weapon, but its benefits and drawbacks are balanced: weapons are powerful but slower than skillful hand-to-hand attacks. Players can also disarm other players to take their weapons.{{r|Gamasutra: Deckbuilding}}

== Development ==

Sloclap, a Parisian [[indie video game development|indie game studio]] composed of former [[Ubisoft Paris]] employees,{{r|Polygon: exUbisoft members}} began to develop its first game in May 2015.{{r|VideoGamer.com: announces}} The team had previously worked on games including ''[[Watch Dogs]]'' and the ''[[Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon]]'' series.{{r|Polygon: exUbisoft members}} They began with the idea that combat should be "fluid" and "dynamic", like a personal choreography. Sloclap expressed this core concept through three internal taglines in their development: "combat is a dance", "movement is your weapon", and "make a move".{{r|Gamasutra: Deckbuilding}} Pierre Tarno, the game's creative director, liked how players could experiment with the combat deck to find a set that works best for them.{{r|Gamasutra: Deckbuilding}} Sloclap plans to closely monitor the [[game balance]] issues of creating overpowered move sets during online play, and plan to monitor this with [[playtesting]].{{r|Gamasutra: Deckbuilding}} ''Absolver'' is built in the [[Unreal Engine 4]] [[game engine]].{{r|VideoGamer.com: announces}} ''Absolver'' was first announced on May 26, 2016,{{r|IGN: announce}} and debuted at the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016|June 2016 Electronic Entertainment Expo]] with [[Devolver Digital]] as its publisher.{{r|IGN: announce}} The game was released on August 29, 2017, for [[PlayStation 4]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] platforms.{{r|Polygon: preview}}

