== Reception ==

[[File:Absolver screenshot Forest.png|thumb|250px|Critics such as Borque praised the game's art style as a departure from industry trends towards [[Hyperrealism (visual arts)|hyperrealism]]]]
{{Video game reviews
| MC = 69/100 (PS4)<br />76/100 (PC){{r|Metacritic: reviews}}
| GI = 6.8/10{{r|GI: review}}
| GSpot = 8/10{{r|GS: review}}
| IGN = 7.6/10{{r|IGN: review}}
| Poly = 8.5/10{{r|Polygon: review}}
<!--| rev1 = ''[[USgamer]]'' | rev1Score = {{rating||5}}<ref name="USgamer: review">{{cite web |last=McCarthy |first=Caty |title=Absolver Review-In-Progress: Prospects, Come out to Play |url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/absolver-review |website=[[USGamer]] |date=August 29, 2017 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>-->
}}

Critics who previewed the game compared its gameplay to that of ''[[Dark Souls]]'' and ''[[Street Fighter]]''.{{r|Polygon: Soulsinspired|PC Gamer: Enigmatic|GamesRadar: timing}} In particular, Sam Prell (''[[GamesRadar]]'') found the ''Souls'' games and ''Absolver'' to share difficult melee fights that emphasize stamina management, and seamless multiplayer that adds both allies and enemies.{{r|GamesRadar: timing}} Critics also noted how the game's simple controls quickly became complex,{{r|Digital Trends: complexity|GamesRadar: timing}} credited in particular to the game's combat deck concept.{{r|Digital Trends: complexity}} Kris Graft (''[[Gamasutra]]'') wrote that the fighting game was "a promising start" and one of the most interesting he has played.{{r|Gamasutra: Deckbuilding}} ''Absolver'' unexpectedly astonished Griffin McElroy (''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''){{emdash}}it was his "biggest surprise" of the 2016 Electronic Entertainment Expo.{{r|Polygon: Soulsinspired}} Sam Prell (''GamesRadar'') was also surprised by the depth of the combat system,{{r|GamesRadar: timing}} and Andrew Tarantola (''[[Engadget]]'') noted the game's deviance from the traditional massively multiplayer online game for its lack of guns,{{r|Engadget: Gunless}} and Brad Borque (''[[Digital Trends]]'') added that ''Absolver'' was quiet compared to other battle-focused games. Borque also complimented ''Absolver''{{'s}} palette and thought of its art style as a welcome break from the [[Hyperrealism (visual arts)|hyperrealism]] of recent games.{{r|Digital Trends: complexity}} Games journalists listed the game among the best in show at the 2016 Electronic Entertainment Expo{{r|Digital Trends: best}} where its other accolades included ''[[GamesRadar]]''{{'s}} "Best Indie Game of E3"{{r|GamesRadar: awards}} and ''[[VentureBeat|GamesBeat]]''{{'s}} "Killer App Killer" for "compelling and/or intuitive gameplay" in an [[Unreal Engine]] game.{{r|GamesBeat: awards}}

''Absolver'' received "mixed or average" reviews for the PS4 version of the game, while the PC version received "generally favorable" reviews from critics, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].{{r|Metacritic: reviews}}

The game was nominated for "Best Action Game" at ''[[PC Gamer]]''{{'}}s 2017 Game of the Year Awards,{{r|PC Gamer: nominees}} and for "Best Fighting Game" in ''[[IGN]]''{{'}}s Best of 2017 Awards.{{r|IGN: 2017}}

